# Payment Rescue

Hackathon design doc. Team: Rachel, Anupama, Caio, Bart, Krzysztof.

## One-liner

A self-serve identifier flow that lets a user make a payment on a plan without logging in. Even users locked out of their account can pay if they can prove who they are with a few lightweight identifiers. An AI risk-scoring layer (Trust Pulse) is a stretch goal, layered on top if hackathon time permits.

## Insight

Affirm has built one auth gate for two trust contracts. Logging in grants capabilities. Paying fulfills an obligation. The gate optimizes for the wrong one: paying is harder than defaulting, and we delete the purest signal in lending, a user trying to pay us when we've made it hard.

The locked-out user is the most extreme case (3.9M users, 89% phone-related). The actual problem is broader: anyone with a payment due, hitting friction.

## Concrete moment

A user with a payment due can't get into their account (lost phone, forgot password, locked-out). They go to Payment Rescue (bookmarked, in a comms footer, or surfaced on the support page). They enter a few lightweight identifiers, pass a verification check, and pay one loan. No full login, no support call.

## What we ship (M1 wedge)

One surface, one mechanism, one moment, one action.

- **Surface:** a self-serve URL (/payment-rescue).
- **Mechanism:** identifier-based form. Trust Pulse risk scoring is a stretch goal layered on top.
- **Moment:** payment due or past due, user can't or won't log in.
- **Action:** make a payment on a plan.

**UX commitments (security posture):**

- Show only the plan being paid. No other plans.
- No wallet inventory shown. The user always adds a new payment instrument for this one payment. No card-on-file surfaced, no instrument-on-file picker.
- Payment instrument options at the pay step:
  - Apple Pay (frontend-mocked in M1; real production v1)
  - Debit card (manual entry) (real backend in M1; charged via payments_connect)
  - Bank account / manual ACH (frontend-mocked in M1; real production v1)
- All instruments are single-use only, not saved to the user's wallet. The session was authorized for one payment, not for account changes. Saving requires explicit opt-in, which is M2.
- No account details, settings, shopping, or recommendations.
- Ephemeral session, scoped to one payment on one loan.
- Confirmation screen ends with a recovery CTA pointing the user at full account recovery (SSPC). Rescue solves the immediate payment; recovery is the long-term fix and we hand the user off explicitly.

## Self-serve identifiers (4 factors, 5 valid pairs)

The user provides any 2 of these factors. At least one factor must be a lookup (Loan ID or Email) so the system can resolve the right user.

| Factor  | Type                 | Notes                                                                 |
|---------|----------------------|-----------------------------------------------------------------------|
| Loan ID | Lookup               | Resolves directly to a loan                                           |
| Email   | Lookup (with OTP)    | Resolves to a user. Triggers an email-OTP step for ownership proof.   |
| DOB     | Confirmation         | Knowledge factor (effectively public)                                 |
| SSN4    | Confirmation         | Knowledge factor (effectively public via breach corpora)              |

**Valid pairs:**

| Pair              | OTP step?       | Security reviewed?          |
|-------------------|-----------------|-----------------------------|
| Email + Loan ID   | Yes (email OTP) | Yes - approved              |
| SSN9 + DOB + ZIP  | No              | Yes - tentatively approved  |

Tim: "The actions we're permitting a user to have are low-risk, so we can have lower-risk items."

**Failure handling:**

- If any factor doesn't validate against records, redirect to customer support. No retry loops beyond standard rate-limit allowances.
- "Failure" includes: pair doesn't match, email OTP wrong/expired, suspected enumeration.
- Phone is not a factor. Doesn't fit the headline persona (89% of lockouts are phone-related).
- last-4 of card is no longer a factor. The payment step uses a freshly added instrument every time, so card-on-file isn't surfaced.
- ZIP is not a user-entered factor. If Trust Pulse ships, it feeds the risk score silently (ZIP-of-record vs. IP geolocation).
- No KBA in M1. Email OTP replaces KBA as the verification step.

## User journeys

Four journeys define what gets built.

### J1: Locked-out Maria (the headline case)

**Trigger.** Maria has a payment due and can't get into her account because she recently changed her phone number. She finds Payment Rescue through a "Can't log in? Pay your loan" affordance on the login screen itself.

**Steps:**
1. Maria lands on /payment-rescue. Form asks for an identifier pair. Default surfaced: Email + Loan ID. Maria fills both and submits.
2. Email OTP step: server sends a 4-digit code to Maria's email. Maria enters it.
3. On OTP pass: payment screen renders with merchant + amount + due date + instrument selector (Apple Pay, debit card, ACH).
4. Maria adds a debit card, taps Pay. Payment succeeds.
5. Confirmation screen shows amount paid, time, next payment + date, and a clear CTA to fully recover the account (start SSPC / set up new device).

**Build:**
- Self-serve form, identifier-pair UI (Email + Loan ID, or SSN9 + DOB + ZIP)
- Lookup endpoint: constant-time, identical-response on miss vs. mismatch, rate-limited
- Multi-loan disambiguation logic (see J2)
- Email OTP send + verify (replaces KBA)
- Scoped session token mint after OTP passes
- Payment screen component (loan card + pay CTA + instrument selector)
- New-instrument flow: Apple Pay (frontend-mocked), debit card (real, charges via payments_connect mocked), ACH (frontend-mocked)
- Failure path: any pair miss, OTP miss, or enumeration suspicion → redirect to customer support phone number
- "Wrong loan?" exit link on payment screen → routes to full login (never to a loan picker)
- Post-payment recovery CTA on the confirmation screen → routes to SSPC entry point

**Stretch enhancement (Trust Pulse):** if the AI risk-scoring service ships, Trust Pulse low risk lets a strong-pair user (Email + Loan ID) fast-path past the OTP step.

### J2: Multi-loan Marcus (the disambiguation case)

Same user-visible flow but with SSN9 + DOB + ZIP. The work is server-side: pick which loan to surface when one user has many.

**Resolution rule:**

| Step | Rule |
|------|------|
| 1 | Resolve user from the identifier pair |
| 2 | List user's loans with payments due (or recently due) |
| 3 | 0 loans due → render the "you're all caught up" state |
| 4 | 1 loan due → surface it |
| 5 | Multiple loans due → most overdue → soonest due |

**UX commitments:**
- User never sees a list of loans.
- All rejection paths return identical responses (no leak of which step failed).
- "Wrong loan?" link on the payment screen routes to full login, never to a loan picker.

## Trust Pulse (stretch goal)

Status: stretch goal for the hackathon. Build only if M1 is rock-solid first.

With KBA removed from M1, the Trust Pulse stretch is now bounded to a single job:

**Risk scoring.** LLM consumes device, IP, geo, ZIP-of-record vs. IP-geo, behavioral, loan-owner profile, request anomalies. Outputs `{score, tier, reasoning}`. Used to gate a fast lane (strong pair like Email + Loan ID with low score → skip the email OTP step).

Trust Pulse does not make the final auth decision. Its score feeds into Affirm's existing risk_framework, which decides allow / escalate / block. AI augments existing decision authority rather than replacing it.

**LLM:** Anthropic Claude (claude-sonnet-4-6 for hackathon, claude-opus-4-7 for max-quality reasoning). Caio has Anthropic API access. Implementation pattern: LangChain ChatAnthropic.

**Demo angle if Trust Pulse ships:** "Trust Pulse scored this request as low-risk: known device, trusted geo. AI advises, risk_framework decides." Without it, the demo is a clean lockout-recovery story without the AI beat.

## Architecture (reuse map, post eng review)

| Need | Real primitive | Hackathon path |
|------|---------------|----------------|
| Self-serve form UX | Form patterns in web-ux/product-flows/src/modules/identity/ and repayment/ | Lift the presentational pieces visually. Do not import the orchestrator containers. |
| Email OTP UI | OTP code-entry pattern in web-ux/product-flows/src/modules/email-otp/ | Lift the visual; build a 4-digit code-entry component. |
| Single-payment step | single-payment-initiated/Component.tsx, single-payment-confirmed/Component.tsx | Lift visual components from web-ux/product-flows/src/modules/repayment/components/. |
| Add-instrument step | web-ux/product-flows/src/modules/add-instrument/ (debit card form) | Lift the debit card form; mock Apple Pay and ACH on the frontend. |
| Logged-out wrapper | identity-app/server is a @affirm/server-mock dev fixture | For the prototype, the mock fixture is fine. |
| Scoped session token | clavis-jwt's JWTController.generateJWT() requires a sessionAri | Hackathon: hand-roll an HS256 token. Production v1: solve via "service session" pattern with Identity team. |
| Flow orchestration | all-the-things/deployable/repayment-experience/ is a stub | Hackathon prototype is REST (Python FastAPI), not gRPC. |
| LLM calls (Trust Pulse only) | ml2/libs/genai/langchain exists | Plain LangChain with Anthropic: `ChatAnthropic(model="claude-sonnet-4-6", temperature=0)`. |
| Payment execution (debit card only) | payments_connect real entry | Mock at the client boundary: stub returns `{status: "succeeded", confirmation_id, ts}`. No real money in the demo. |
| Rate limiting | affirm.counters2.client.client_v1.check_ratelimit_and_increment_v1 | Mandatory for the demo to defend the lookup endpoint against enumeration. |

No new service. We compose existing pieces and fill in the empty repayment-experience deployable with the Payment Rescue RPCs.

## Hackathon prototype (2 days, this week)

**Stack:** Python FastAPI service + Vite + React + Tailwind frontend, both running locally. REST API, not gRPC. No imports from web-ux/product-flows. Single hackathon repo at payment-rescue-hackathon/.

**Core build (must ship for the demo):**

| Item | Owner | Real or mocked |
|------|-------|----------------|
| Frontend flow: identifier form → email OTP → payment screen → success/blocked | Krzysztof | Real composition, mock backend calls where needed |
| Backend handler (Python FastAPI): POST /api/lookup, /api/otp/send, /api/otp/verify, /api/pay. HS256 token mint. | Caio | Real handler, real token, mock payments_connect |
| Email OTP send: SendGrid HTTP API direct | Krzysztof / Rachel | Real email to test inboxes |
| Payment instrument flows: Apple Pay (frontend-mocked), debit card (real backend), ACH (frontend-mocked) | Krzysztof | Debit card real on backend; Apple Pay + ACH frontend-only |
| Customer-support redirect surface | Rachel | Real |
| Three demo scenarios scripted: J1 Maria (success), J2 Marcus (multi-loan), J3 Eve (blocked) | All | Scripted with seeded payloads |

**Stretch build (only if core is rock-solid):**

| Item | Owner | What it adds |
|------|-------|--------------|
| Trust Pulse Python service: risk scoring via LangChain ChatAnthropic | Bart | AI risk-scoring narrative on stage; fast lane for low-risk attempts |

**What gets cut from the prototype:** real MessageTemplate registration, real payments_connect integration, fraud-middleware bypass, production observability, real device fingerprinting, KBA flow, magic-link entry path, real Apple Pay / ACH backends.

